@mirjak As discussed in [#424 ]  the path ID is a variable-length integer with a maximum value of 2^32-1. This means that to store the maximum value, 8 bytes of space are required.  The encoding of 2^32-1 is 0xc0000000ffffffff.

If we limit the maximum value of the path ID to 2^30-1, then we only need 4 bytes to store it. 2^30-1 should be sufficient for the path ID, and 4 bytes also meet the requirements for nonce calculation.


https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9000.html#name-variable-length-integer-enc

